    "action": "Final Answer",
    "action_input": "Double descent refers to a counterintuitive phenomenon observed in machine learning where the performance of a model first gets worse and then suddenly improves as the complexity of the model is increased beyond a certain point. It contrasts with the traditional view where increasing model complexity monotonically increases the risk of overfitting after surpassing the optimal capacity. Imagine training a model as a hike along a mountain ridge: initially, as you climb (increase complexity), the risk of falling (overfitting) increases. Just when you think you're at the peak risk, the ridge unexpectedly levels out, allowing you to climb further without falling. This is where performance improves again despite higher complexity. This phenomenon is particularly noticeable in regimes where the number of parameters is larger than the number of data points."
}
