    "action": "Final Answer",
    "action_input": "Python strings are sequences of characters that are used to store and manipulate text data. They can be enclosed in single quotes ('...'), double quotes (\"...\"), or triple quotes ('''...''' or \"\"\"...\"\"\") for multi-line strings. Strings are immutable, meaning once they are created, their content cannot be altered. However, you can perform a variety of operations on them such as concatenation (combining strings), slicing (extracting parts of strings), and applying various methods like .upper() to convert to uppercase or .lower() to convert to lowercase. To access a single character, you use square brackets with the index of the character, remembering that indexing starts at 0. For example, in the string 'Hello', 'H' is at index 0. Strings also come with a set of built-in methods for common tasks like .startswith(), .endswith(), .replace(), and .split(). These powerful features allow you to handle text in a very flexible and efficient manner in Python."
}
